Learning Goals:
• Learn to work individually and collaboratively on written and oral projects;
• Develop a theoretical understanding of the long history of literary
games as it is constituted in time from the 13th century through the 21st
century;
• Understand and develop literary, cultural, and critical analysis of historical
and contemporary literary game media and an understanding of transmedia;
• Understand and write reflective analysis in comparing theories of media with the
practice of playing, analyzing, and on occasion making media;
• Demonstrate the ability to conduct interdisciplinary and multimodal research and
write interdisciplinary and multimodal research;
• Demonstrate the ability to compose logical media analysis on literary/cultural
materials for multiple audiences;
• Learn to present on one’s creative/critical projects to a peer audience both individually and as a
group.

Week 1-3
Introduction, diagnostic exam, placement exam;
Fundamentals of music: overtone series, key signatures, scales, intervals;
Triads and seventh chords;
Inversions;
Roman Numerals, Figured Bass;
Principles of rhythm; Introduction to species counterpoint
Week 4-6
First and second species counterpoint;
Melody, harmony and rhythm in context;
Harmonic analysis with I and V;
Cadence types;
Neighbor tones, passing tones
Week 7-9
V7 chord;
Tonic expansion;
I6, V6 and viio6;
Harmonizing melodic and bass fragments using these chords;
3rd species counterpoint;
Cadential 6
4
Elision of Cadence
Week 10-12
Predominant Harmonies;
Phrygian Half-cadence;
Embellishing tones;
Plagal and Deceptive Cadence;
Identifying a V/V secondary dominant;
Tonic Expansion;
Dominant Expansion
Week 13-15
Composing for String Quartet;
Texture and other stylistic concerns;
String Techniques;
Final Performance!
